<section class="section narrow">
  <h2>The <em class="accent-em">long version</em></h2>
  <p>I spent most of my career in automation engineering. I was good at it. By the end I was also missing the part of me that had wanted to make games since I was a kid — not as a hobby on the side, but as the thing I was supposed to be doing. The pull toward this never quite went away, and at some point it got louder than the reasons not to. I went indie in 2025.</p>
  <aside class="before-this">
    <p class="lbl">Before this</p>
    <p class="line">Seven years in automation engineering.</p>
    <p class="line dim">Dev → team lead → tech lead.</p>
  </aside>
  <p>Most days now I'm in Unreal — writing C++ when something needs to be load-bearing, Blueprints when it doesn't yet, and Blender or Substance when the materials need attention. The engineering instincts pay their rent every day, but I'm here for the games. Half the work is cutting things; the other half is figuring out which half is which.</p>
  <p>I make tutorial content on the side because explaining things is how I actually learn them. There's a UE5 instructor certification on my desk this year too.</p>
</section>

<div class="pull-quote">
  <blockquote>The pull toward making games never quite went away. At some point it just got louder than the reasons not to.</blockquote>
</div>

